article.description:
Yolanda Griffith scored 17 points to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to a 77-69 win Friday night over the Los Angeles Sparks in the opening round of the WNBA's Western
Conference finals.
article.headline: Sacramento seals win at free-throw line
article.linkText: Monarchs blow lead, then hold off Sparks for win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Yolanda Griffith was too much for Lisa Leslie and the Los Angeles Sparks.

Friday, Sept. 5
In the regular season, Mwadi Mabika, Tamecka Dixon and Nikki Teasley averaged 39 points. On Friday, the perimeter trio combined for just 22, and that was a big factor in L.A.'s loss.

When you rely on your starters, they have to be consistent -- and avoid foul trouble. Instead, Mabika, Dixon and Teasley went 7-for-31 (23 percent) from the field. Mabika was 3 of 17, and Teasley (1 of 5) didn't hit her first field goal until 1:25 remained.

Still, Sacramento deserves a lot of credit. The Monarchs played their game, got four players in double figures and came up huge at the foul line, hitting 17 of 19 free throws after shooting a league-worst 67.9 percent at the line in the regular season.

Ticha Penicheiro also was excellent. She averaged 2.3 points in the first round, but had 16 Friday, including a 3-pointer that regained Sacramento's lead for good after L.A. had pulled ahead 62-60.

Griffith scored 17 points to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to a 77-69 win Friday night over Los Angeles in the opening round of the WNBA's Western Conference finals.

The Monarchs squandered a sizable lead, briefly lost it in the second half, then played steady down the stretch to hold off the two-time defending champions in front of a raucous crowd of nearly 14,000.

"It was great, our fans have been behind us all year," Monarchs forward Tangela Smith said. "They were huge for us tonight."

The best-of-three series returns to Los Angeles, where Game 2 will be played Sunday followed by a third game Monday, if necessary.

Trailing 62-60 with 6:39 remaining, Ticha Penicheiro made a 3-pointer and followed with another basket, igniting a 7-0 run to give Sacramento the lead for good.

"It was a great atmosphere tonight, that's what home court advantage is all about," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said.

"But now we're going back to LA where we worked our tails off all year to get that home court advantage."

Lisa Leslie was dominant at times for Los Angeles. She had 25 points, seven rebounds and four blocks. DeLisha Milton had 20 points and seven rebounds.

Penicheiro, the star of Sacramento's series-winning victory earlier in the week against Houston, had 16 points and five assists.

Smith had 14 points and 10 rebounds, while DeMya Walker added 11 points.

"The Monarchs came out with a lot of energy in the first half and we were a little flat," Leslie said.

"They were getting second-half points and crashing the boards. It's tough battling those three all game, Griffith, Smith and Walker."
